\Rightarrow 16\sqrt{x}(3+\sqrt{x})dy &= \frac{(4-\sqrt{9+\sqrt{x}})dx}{7+\sqrt{x}}
\end{align*}
This looks like a good candidate for substitution. Let $u = 9+\sqrt{x}$, so that $x = (u-9)^2$. Then, $dx = 2(u-9)du$, and we can rewrite the differential equation as:
\begin{align*}
16(u-9)dy &= \frac{(4-\sqrt{u})2(u-9)du}{7+\sqrt{(u-9)^2+9}} \\
\Rightarrow 8(u-9)dy &= \frac{(4-\sqrt{u})du}{\sqrt{u+9}}
\end{align*}
Now, we can use separation of variables:
\begin{align*}
\frac{8(u-9)}{(4-\sqrt{u})}\frac{dy}{du} &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{u+9}} \\
\Rightarrow 8\int\frac{(u-9)}{(4-\sqrt{u})}du &= \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{u+9}}dy \\
\Rightarrow 8\int\frac{(u-9)(4+\sqrt{u})}{7}du &= 2\sqrt{u+9}+C
\end{align*}
where $C$ is the constant of integration. We can simplify the integral on the left-hand side by using long division or partial fractions:
\begin{align*}
\frac{(u-9)(4+\sqrt{u})}{7} &= \frac{4}{7}(u-9) + \frac{1}{7}(u-9)^{3/2} \\
&= \frac{4}{7}(u-9) + \frac{1}{7}(x-256)^{3/4}
\end{align*}
where we substituted back $x = (u-9)^2 = (x-256)^{1/2}$. Plugging this into the previous equation and solving for $y$, we get:
\begin{align*}
8\left[\frac{4}{7}(u-9) + \frac{1}{7}(x-256)^{3/4}\right] &= 2\sqrt{u+9}+C \\
\Rightarrow y &= \frac{1}{8}\left[\frac{2}{3}\sqrt{u+9} + \frac{1}{21}(x-256)^{3/4}\sqrt{u+9}\right] + \frac{C}{8}
\end{align*}
Using the initial condition $y(0) = \sqrt{7}$, we can solve for $C$:
