We can write the equations of the lines in vector form as:
\begin{align*}
L_1: \vec{r} &= \lambda \hat{i} \\
L_2: \vec{r} &= \hat{k} + \mu \hat{j} \\
L_3: \vec{r} &= \hat{i} + \hat{j} + v \hat{k}
\end{align*}
Let $Q$ be a point on $L_2$. We want to find if there exist points $P$ on $L_1$ and $R$ on $L_3$ such that $P$, $Q$, and $R$ are collinear. This means that the vectors $\vec{PQ}$ and $\vec{QR}$ are parallel, which implies that $\vec{PQ}$ and $\vec{QR}$ are scalar multiples of each other. Let $t$ be the scalar multiple, so we have:
\begin{align*}
\vec{PQ} &= t \vec{QR} \\
\vec{PQ} &= \vec{Q} - \vec{P} \\
\vec{QR} &= \vec{R} - \vec{Q}
\end{align*}
Substituting the equations of the lines, we get:
\begin{align*}
\vec{PQ} &= t \vec{QR} \\
\lambda \hat{i} - \vec{Q} &= t (\hat{i} + \hat{j} + v \hat{k} - \vec{Q}) \\
\vec{QR} &= \vec{R} - \vec{Q} \\
\hat{i} + \hat{j} + v \hat{k} - \vec{Q} &= t (\vec{Q} - \hat{k})
\end{align*}
We can write these equations as a system of linear equations in the variables $\lambda$, $\mu$, $v$, and $t$:
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= t (\mu - 1) \\
-\mu \hat{j} &= t (\mu - 1) \hat{i} \\
v \hat{k} &= t (\mu - 1) \hat{i} + (t-1) \hat{j} \\
\end{align*}
The first equation implies that $t \neq 0$, so we can divide both sides by $t$:
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \mu - 1 \\
-\mu \hat{j} &= (\mu - 1) \hat{i} \\
v \hat{k} &= (\mu - 1) \hat{i} + (t-1) \hat{j} \\
\end{align*}
The second equation implies that $\mu \neq 1$, so we can divide both sides by $-\mu$:
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \mu - 1 \\
\hat{j} &= \frac{1}{\mu} (\mu - 1) \hat{i} \\
v \hat{k} &= \frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} \hat{i} + (t-1) \hat{j} \\
\end{align*}
The second equation implies that $\hat{i}$ and $\hat{j}$ are parallel, so $\hat{i} = k \hat{j}$ for some constant $k$. Substituting this into the third equation, we get:
\begin{align*}
v \hat{k} &= \frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} k \hat{j} + (t-1) \hat{j} \\
v \hat{k} &= \left(\frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} k + t - 1\right) \hat{j} \\
\end{align*}
Since $\hat{j}$ and $\hat{k}$ are orthogonal, the coefficient of $\hat{j}$ must be zero, so we have:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} k + t - 1 &= 0 \\
\frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} k &= 1 - t \\
k &= \frac{\mu}{\mu - 1} (1 - t)
\end{align*}
Substituting this into the second equation, we get:
\begin{align*}
\hat{j} &= \frac{1}{\mu} (\mu - 1) k \hat{i} \\
\hat{j} &= \frac{1}{\mu} (\mu - 1) \cdot \frac{\mu}{\mu - 1} (1 - t) \hat{i} \\
\hat{j} &= (1 - t) \hat{i}
\end{align*}
Therefore, $\hat{i}$ and $\hat{j}$ are parallel if and only if $t = 1$. If $t = 1$, then we have:
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \mu - 1 \\
\hat{j} &= 0 \\
v \hat{k} &= \frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} \hat{i}
\end{align*}
The second equation implies that $\mu \neq 0$, so we can divide both sides by $\mu$:
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \mu - 1 \\
0 &= \mu - 1 \\
v \hat{k} &= \frac{\mu - 1}{\mu} \hat{i}
\end{align*}
Therefore, $\mu = 1$, $v = 0$, and $\lambda = 0$. This means that $Q = \hat{k}$, and we can take $P = \vec{0}$ and $R = \hat{i} + \hat{j}$, so the answer is $\boxed{\textbf{(B) } \hat{k}}$.

