Let $p$ be the probability that the roots of the quadratic are real and equal. Then, by Vieta's formulas, the roots are real and equal if and only if $\alpha$ is even and $\beta$ is a perfect square. Thus, we want to find $p$ in terms of the probabilities of $\alpha$ being even and $\beta$ being a perfect square.

The probability that $\alpha$ is even is
\begin{align*}
P(\alpha \text{ is even}) &= P(\text{first toss is H and second toss is H}) + P(\text{first toss is T and second toss is T}) \\
&= \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 \\
&= \frac{5}{9}.
\end{align*}

The probability that $\beta$ is a perfect square is
\begin{align*}
P(\beta \text{ is a perfect square}) &= P(\text{both tosses are H}) + P(\text{both tosses are T}) + P(\text{one toss is H and one toss is T}) \\
&= \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 + 2\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)\left(\frac{1}{3}\right) \\
&= \frac{5}{9}.
\end{align*}

Therefore, we have
\begin{align*}
p &= P(\alpha \text{ is even and } \beta \text{ is a perfect square}) \\
&= P(\alpha \text{ is even}) \cdot P(\beta \text{ is a perfect square}) \\
&= \frac{5}{9} \cdot \frac{5}{9} \\
&= \boxed{\textbf{(A) } \frac{40}{81}}.
\end{align*}

