Let $\frac{2+3 z+4 z^{2}}{2-3 z+4 z^{2}}=k$ where $k$ is a real number. Then we have
\begin{align*}
2+3z+4z^2 &= k(2-3z+4z^2)\\
(4-k)z^2 + (3k+3)z + (2-2k) &= 0
\end{align*}
Since $z$ has non-zero imaginary part, the quadratic equation above has two distinct roots. Thus, the discriminant must be positive:
\begin{align*}
(3k+3)^2 - 4(4-k)(2-2k) &> 0\\
9k^2 + 6k + 9 &> 0\\
k &> -1
\end{align*}
Now, we have
\begin{align*}
|z|^2 &= z\overline{z}\\
&= \frac{1}{2}\left[(z+\overline{z})^2 - (z-\overline{z})^2i^2\right]\\
&= \frac{1}{2}\left[(z+\overline{z})^2 + (z-\overline{z})^2\right]\\
&= \frac{1}{2}\left[4\text{Re}(z)^2 + 4\text{Im}(z)^2\right]\\
&= 2|z|^2
\end{align*}
Therefore, $|z|^2 = \frac{1}{2}|z|^2 > 0$. Combining this with the fact that $k>-1$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{2+3 z+4 z^{2}}{2-3 z+4 z^{2}} &= \frac{(4-k)z^2 + (3k+3)z + (2-2k)}{(4-k)z^2 - (3k-3)z + (2+2k)}\\
&= \frac{(3k+3)z + (2-2k)}{-(3k-3)z + (2+2k)}\\
&= \frac{(k+1)z + \frac{2-2k}{k+1}}{(k-1)z + \frac{2+2k}{k-1}}
\end{align*}
Since this expression is real, the imaginary part of the numerator must be zero. Thus, we have
\begin{align*}
\text{Im}\left[(k+1)z + \frac{2-2k}{k+1}\right] &= 0\\
\text{Im}(k+1)z &= \text{Im}\left(\frac{2-2k}{k+1}\right)\\
\text{Im}(k+1)z &= \frac{-4}{k+1}
\end{align*}
Since $z$ has non-zero imaginary part, we have $\text{Im}(k+1) \neq 0$. Thus, we can solve for $z$:
\begin{align*}
z &= \frac{-4}{\text{Im}(k+1)(k+1)i}\\
&= \frac{4}{(k+1)^2}\cdot\frac{1}{i}\\
&= \frac{4i}{(k+1)^2}
\end{align*}
Finally, we have
\begin{align*}
|z|^2 &= \left|\frac{4i}{(k+1)^2}\right|^2\\
&= \frac{16}{(k+1)^4}\\
&= \frac{16}{(2+\sqrt{5})^2}\\
&\approx \boxed{2.20}
\end{align*}

