y &= \frac{1}{12}\left(\frac{12}{\pi}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) - \frac{1}{144}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) + Ce^{-12x}\right)
\end{align*}
Using the initial condition $y(0) = 0$, we get $C = \frac{1}{144}$, so
\begin{align*}
y(x) &= \frac{1}{12}\left(\frac{12}{\pi}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) - \frac{1}{144}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) + \frac{1}{144}e^{-12x}\right) \\
&= \frac{1}{\pi}\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) - \frac{1}{12^2}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) + \frac{1}{12^2}e^{-12x}
\end{align*}
(A) $y(x)$ is an increasing function for $x > 0$. To see this, note that $y'(x) = \frac{1}{12}\left(\frac{\pi}{12}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) + 12e^{-12x}\right)$. Since $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right)$ is always positive for $x > 0$ and $12e^{-12x}$ is always decreasing, $y'(x)$ is positive for $x > 0$, which means $y(x)$ is increasing for $x > 0$.

(B) $y(x)$ is a decreasing function for $x < 0$. To see this, note that $y'(x) = \frac{1}{12}\left(\frac{\pi}{12}\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right) + 12e^{-12x}\right)$. Since $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{12}x\right)$ is always negative for $x < 0$ and $12e^{-12x}$ is always decreasing, $y'(x)$ is negative for $x < 0$, which means $y(x)$ is decreasing for $x < 0$.

