\begin{align*}
\sqrt{1+\cos(2x)} &= \sqrt{2} \left(x - \left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor \pi \right) \\
\sqrt{1+\cos(2x)} &= \sqrt{2}x - \sqrt{2}\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor \pi
\end{align*}

Squaring both sides, we get

\begin{align*}
1+\cos(2x) &= 2x^2 - 2x\sqrt{2}\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor \pi + 2\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor^2 \pi^2 \\
\cos(2x) &= 2x^2 - 2x\sqrt{2}\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor \pi + 2\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor^2 \pi^2 - 1
\end{align*}

Now, we consider the three intervals separately.

For $x \in \left(-\frac{3\pi}{2}, -\frac{\pi}{2}\right)$, we have $\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor = -2$, so the equation becomes

\begin{align*}
\cos(2x) &= 2x^2 + 4x\sqrt{2}\pi + 8\pi^2 - 1 \\
&= 2\left(x+\frac{\sqrt{2}\pi}{2}\right)^2 + 8\pi^2 - 1
\end{align*}

Since $-3\pi < x < -\pi$, we have $-\frac{5\pi}{2} < x+\frac{\sqrt{2}\pi}{2} < -\frac{3\pi}{2}$, so $\cos(2x) < 0$. Therefore, there are no solutions in this interval.

For $x \in \left(-\frac{\pi}{2}, \frac{\pi}{2}\right)$, we have $\left\lfloor \frac{x+\frac{\pi}{2}}{\pi} \right\rfloor = 0$, so the equation becomes

\begin{align*}
\cos(2x) &= 2x^2 - 1
\end{align*}

Since $-\frac{\pi}{2} < x < \frac{\pi}{2}$, we have $-1 < \cos(2x) < 1$, so there are two solutions in this interval.

